<DOC><DOCNO> DOE1-68-0827 </DOCNO><TEXT>The author traces the history of crises in the petroleum industry, startingin the 1920s, but concentrating on the 1970s to the present. He explainsmany of the phenomena of the years prior to October 1973 (the oil embargo),after which oil prices increased 5-fold in only 3 months. There was relativecalm after the events of 1973-74, until 1977, at which time Saudi Arabiaand the United Arab Emirates effected a compromise for OPEC price increasesyearly of 10%. After the fall of the Shah of Iran in 1979, decreasingthe world's petroleum supply, Arabian light crude went from about $13to almost $35/bbl, strengthening the spot market. The average price of$17.26/bbl in 1979 climbed 66% to $28.67 bbl in 1980. In the second halfof 1981, oversupply forced a generalized drop in prices. The latter partof the article discusses the most significant negative effects of themarket decline, which began in 1981 and reached bottom in 1986. 3 references,3 figures, 2 tables.</TEXT></DOC>